description:
file: rust/lichen-sim/src/client.rs:229-240

When recv_msg() receives a message with length > MAX_MSG_LEN, it returns an error but leaves the connection in a desynced state:

```rust
async fn recv_msg(&mut self) -> Result<Vec<u8>, SimError> {
    let mut len_bytes = [0u8; 4];
    self.reader.read_exact(&mut len_bytes).await?;
    let len = u32::from_le_bytes(len_bytes) as usize;
    if len > MAX_MSG_LEN {
        return Err(SimError::Protocol("message too large"));  // BUG: 4-byte header consumed, body not
    }
    // ...
}
```

The 4-byte length header has been consumed, but the message body is left unread in the stream. The next call to recv_msg() will interpret body bytes as the length header, causing garbage parsing.

Compare to Python sim_client.py which closes the stream on protocol errors (lines 363-376).

Fix: Either consume/discard the message body before returning error, or close the connection to prevent further use.
